-- Duke Beats North Carolina, Rutgers Wins With Four-Point Final-Second Play
-- B y   R o b   G l o s t e r
-- 2011-02-10T05:01:47Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-10/duke-beats-north-carolina-rutgers-wins-with-four-point-final-second-play.html
Nolan Smith had a career-high 34
points to lead  Duke University  to a 79-73 win against the
University of North Carolina in men’s college basketball.  Rutgers University  got four points in the game’s final second to
defeat Villanova University.  Duke, the reigning National Collegiate Athletic Association
champion, outscored the visiting Tar Heels 50-30 in the second
half after trailing by 14 points at halftime.  Duke, which leads the Atlantic Coast Conference, improved
to 22-2 overall and 9-1 in conference play. North Carolina fell
to 17-6 overall and 7-2 in ACC play.  Smith and Seth Curry, who finished with 22 points, combined
for 40 points in the second half as Duke won its 33rd straight
home game at Cameron Indoor Stadium in Durham,  North Carolina .  Tyler Zeller had 24 points for North Carolina, which won
the national title in 2008-2009.  Jonathan Mitchell had a four-point play with 0.8 seconds
left in the game to give Rutgers a 77-76 win against Villanova
in Big East conference play. Rutgers (13-11 overall, 4-8
conference) dropped the Wildcats to 19-5 overall and 7-4 in the
conference.  Mitchell, who had a career-high 25 points to lead the
Scarlet Knights, was fouled by Corey Fisher while hitting a 3-
point shot in the game’s final second. He hit the free throw to
complete a rare four-point play and give Rutgers the victory.  Fisher had 23 points to lead Villanova, which lost despite
shooting 56 percent from the field and going 8-of-16 from 3-
point range. Rutgers, which hit 47 percent of its shots, trailed
by 10 points with 2:42 left in the game at the Louis Brown
Athletic Center in Piscataway,  New Jersey .  Georgetown Defeats Syracuse  Jason Clark scored six of his 12 points in the final 2:38
and Austin Freeman had 14 points as  Georgetown University 
defeated host Syracuse University 64-56 in another Big East
game. Georgetown improved to 19-5 overall and 8-4 in conference
play, while Syracuse fell to 20-5 and 7-5 in Big East contests.  Also in the Big East last night,  Notre Dame  improved to 20-
4 overall and 9-3 in Big East games with an 89-79 overtime win
against visiting Louisville, which dropped to 18-6 overall and
7-4 in conference play.  To contact the reporter on this story:
